  <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    A thorough analysis of&amp;nbsp;the Business, Logical or Technical&amp;nbsp;level&amp;nbsp;&lt;em>&lt;strong>perspective&lt;/strong>&lt;/em> of&#xD;
    the IT architecture is done to ensure that the define architecture fits in with the its wider context, with the rest of&#xD;
    the enterprise.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;em>Prior&lt;/em> to this analysis the IT architecture has been reviewed ensuring that it is complete and consistent&#xD;
    (normally an IT&amp;nbsp;architect&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong>peer review&lt;/strong>) &lt;em>and&lt;/em> a review of&amp;nbsp;the content of the&#xD;
    architecture in terms of how accurately it captures the business (normally involving stakeholders that have intimate&#xD;
    knowledge of the business, a &lt;strong>stakeholder review&lt;/strong>). This is accomplished through an architecture review:&#xD;
    &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot; href=&quot;./../../../UAM/tasks/uam_review_architecture_3FA51112.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;_hQm4MMkiEdyU89e0dKAsrw&quot;>Task: Review an Architecture&lt;/a>.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    This &lt;em>analysis&lt;/em> assumes that the IT architecture is complete and accurate (i.e. the &lt;em>review&lt;/em> has been&#xD;
    completed) and now takes a step back from the IT architecture and looks at the larger context, proposed solutions,&#xD;
    implications of these solutions, and how it all fits into the enterprise's business strategy, IT strategy, technology&#xD;
    and other standards,&amp;nbsp;and other plans and objectives. This analysis is slightly different for each of the levels.&#xD;
    Not only are the participants different, the focus and objectives of the analysis at the Business level are much&#xD;
    different that those at the Technical level.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The&amp;nbsp;analysis looks at one of the levels of the IT architecture (i.e. a completely defined&amp;nbsp;perspective), which&#xD;
    in turn dictates the set of stakeholders involved:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Business level&lt;/strong> - mainly business&amp;nbsp;stakeholders involved, with some technical stakeholders;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Logical / Technical level&lt;/strong> -&amp;nbsp;mainly technical stakeholders, with some business stakeholders&#xD;
        (business experts).&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Each of these levels of analysis will naturally have a different focus. Typically the focus for each level are:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Business level&lt;/strong>&amp;nbsp;- education, review and feedback on business processes, and how they fit into&#xD;
        the larger context. Optimizations and other opportunities are examined&amp;nbsp;and decided;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Logical / Technical level&lt;/strong> - provide education and solicit feedback on logical / technical&#xD;
        solutions, any implications of the solutions or technologies, how they fit into the larger enterprise context and&#xD;
        if any optimizations or other opportunities are possible.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Decisions and actions are documented, assigned&amp;nbsp;and tracked.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
</org.eclipse.epf.uma:ContentDescription>
